    'motion-with-restraint':
      '---\ntitle: "Motion with restraint in technical product surfaces"\ndescription: "How subtle animation can improve hierarchy, pacing, and confidence without making the interface feel ornamental."\npublishedAt: "2026-03-31"\nfeatured: false\ntags:\n  - Design Systems\n  - Framer Motion\n  - UI\n---\n\n## Motion should confirm structure\n\nMotion is useful when it tells the user what changed, what belongs together, or\nwhere attention should land next. It becomes noise when it tries to entertain.\n\nAt Sonicverse we bias toward:\n\n- short distances\n- soft easing\n- reduced-motion respect\n- meaningful grouping\n\n<Callout title="Rule of thumb" tone="info">\n  If animation cannot explain itself in product terms, it usually does not belong in\n  the system.\n</Callout>\n\n## Where subtle motion helps most\n\n### Entry and reveal\n\nSmall reveal animations help sections feel sequenced instead of dumped onto the page.\n\n### Hover feedback\n\nCards and actions can lift slightly to confirm interactivity without shouting.\n\n### Dense interfaces\n\nWhen pages contain structured data, motion can help users maintain context as\nelements load or reflow.\n\n## The premium effect\n\nRestrained motion often feels more technical and more expensive than aggressive\nanimation. It suggests confidence in the structure, not dependence on spectacle.\n',
